    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our method builds upon the Chemprop architecture developed by Yang et al. Chemprop consists of a directed MPNN and a feedforward neural network (FFNN) readout. The directed MPNN constructs a learned vector representation, or molecular fingerprint, from a given molecular graph by message passing. Atom and bond features are combined through the message passing steps to generate the learned molecular fingerprint. In the application of directed message passing, the messages and hidden states of the network are associated with directed edges (bonds) instead of nodes (atoms). Chemprop-IR uses an extension of the Chemprop network structure that specializes in the prediction of IR spectra, in the form of 1801 output elements.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes Chemprop-IR as an extension of Chemprop that specializes in IR spectral prediction with 1801 output elements representing absorbances at fixed wavenumber positions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acs_jcim_1c00055",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does the chemprop-IR architecture extend the base chemprop message passing neural network with new spectral features?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:10:41.626313+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In this paper, we investigate the application of Chemprop, a state-of-the-art MPNN, toward the prediction of IR spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "Chemprop is explicitly named as the base MPNN architecture used in this work.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acs_jcim_1c00055",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "chemprop",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:10:41.626313+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Chemprop-IR has been developed as a software package for the prediction of IR spectra through the use of machine learning. This work serves the dual purpose of providing a trained general-purpose model for the prediction of IR spectra with ease and providing the Chemprop-IR software framework for the training of new models.",
      "asbval:note": "Chemprop-IR is the main software package developed in this paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acs_jcim_1c00055",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "chemprop-IR",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:10:41.626313+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The Chemprop-IR software is available through a public repository with Git Hub. An archived version of the software and the trained models associated with this publication are shared through Zenodo. In this repository, the trained models for the computed spectra and for experimental spectra are provided, allowing predictions of new spectra in any of the supported phases. The software provides tools for calculating ensemble uncertainty for predicted spectra and for calculating SIS between predictions and reference spectra. The software enables the training of new models from input spectra, using such features as the SID loss function and spectrum normalization by specified absorbance ranges.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper provides trained models and software for training new models, but does not explicitly describe a 'spectral features module' as a distinct compilable component. The architecture includes spectral loss functions (SID) and normalization techniques, but the card's phrasing of 'spectral features module' is not explicitly named in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acs_jcim_1c00055",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "instantiated chemprop-IR model with spectral features module successfully compiled",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:10:41.626313+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The initial input to the model is a SMILES string, which is interpreted as a 2D molecular graph. Each bond and heavy atom in the molecule is used to generate a vector of atom or bond features. The bond and atom features are used to generate hidden states of size 2200 at each of the directed edges. In each message passing step, the hidden states are updated according to the directed message passing procedure described by Yang et al. Following the message passing steps, atom vectors are generated from the associated directed edge hidden states. The atom vectors are averaged to form a molecular fingerprint vector of size 2200. The phase of the molecule is introduced to the molecular fingerprint vector following message passing. The molecular vector following this concatenation is size 2205 for experimental spectra models and 2200 for computed spectra models. After phase feature concatenation, the resulting vector is fed to a FFNN for readout of the model results. For each intermediate layer in the FFNN, the produced vector size is 2200. The final layer of the FFNN provides an output size of 1801.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the forward pass in detail: SMILES input \u2192 2D graph \u2192 message passing \u2192 molecular fingerprint (2200 or 2205 elements) \u2192 FFNN \u2192 output tensor of 1801 elements (absorbances at wavenumber positions).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acs_jcim_1c00055",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "forward pass output tensor from sample molecule verification",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:10:41.626313+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card frames the task as 'reconstructing' the architecture, which implies implementation/coding. The paper is a published research article describing the architecture and providing trained models, not a tutorial or implementation guide. The card's expected outputs suggest a coding/engineering task, but the paper is primarily a scientific publication.",
        "The card's phrasing 'spectral features module' is not standard terminology in the paper. The paper refers to 'spectral loss functions' (SID, TMSE), 'spectral metrics' (SIS), and 'normalization techniques', but not a discrete 'spectral features module'."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 2,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:10:41.626313+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In Chemprop-IR, molecules are encoded using a directed message passing neural network, allowing for molecule latent representations to be learned and optimized for the task of spectral predictions... The phase of the molecule is introduced to the molecular fi ngerprint vector following message passing.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes phase features (one-hot vector of size 5 for experimental spectra) concatenated to molecular fingerprint, but does not detail a separate 'spectral feature extraction step' as a distinct pipeline module. The paper focuses on how phase information is incorporated into the MPNN fingerprint, not on extracting spectral features from spectra themselves. The card's framing suggests feature extraction from spectral data, but the paper describes feature engineering for molecular input and phase metadata.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acs_jcim_1c00055",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "What are the spectral features that chemprop-IR implements to extend the base chemprop architecture for infrared spectral prediction tasks?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:10:58.919926+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
